    "title": "The Ownership Stack, Not the Ride",
    "summary": "The load-bearing problem is not whether robotaxi miles get cheaper. It is that Tesla-scale autonomy turns the privately owned vehicle into a platform node whose OEM can absorb insurance settlement, supervised-mile subscription revenue, and eventual fleet dispatch—collapsing the multi-party ownership economy (lender, insurer, adjuster, dealer, household) into a single vertically integrated counterparty while household demand is already fracturing under payment stress.",
    "mechanism": "Separate demand from delivery: household car demand is weakening on payment refusal and utilization math, while Tesla simultaneously sells supervised autonomy into owned vehicles and operates a limited robotaxi fleet in Texas. The binding constraint is not fleet scale but platform capture—telematics plus OEM direct settlement disintermediates the adjuster layer, and supervised FSD keeps the car in the driveway while harvesting miles toward eventual service conversion. The neglected stakeholder is every intermediary whose margin assumes the human driver remains the legal and economic subject of the vehicle.",
    "claimedDelta": "Moves the problem from 'will Americans switch to robotaxis?' to 'which layers of the car-ownership stack break first when the OEM becomes insurer, claims authority, and fleet operator on the same VIN'—grounded in live but limited robotaxi deployment, operational friction in Texas, and telematics-driven claims disintermediation rather than hypothetical full autonomy adoption.",
