  "candidate": {
    "id": "sol_cb_balance_sheet_parking",
    "agenomeId": "ag_blindside",
    "title": "Balance-Sheet Parking for the Car-Dependency Stack",
    "summary": "Cheaper miles fail because households optimize a bundled balance-sheet object—secured debt, insurable collateral, registrable asset, spatial anchor—not trip price. The neglected stakeholder is the car-dependency industry (captive lenders, dealers, insurers, OEM finance, registration infrastructure) whose revenue requires that bundle to stay on household balance sheets. Instead of waiting for autonomy to undercut ownership, unbundle obligation from use by parking the bundle inside industry-held vehicle trusts while households hold revocable mobility rights.",
    "mechanism": "A regulated balance-sheet parking trust holds title, lien, insurance policy, and garage/driveway spatial anchor as a single industry-managed collateral package. Households exit to a usage-rights subscription priced on monthly obligation relief, not per-mile fare. Captive lenders and dealers retain securitization and service-contract economics; insurers price the trust via telematics-native loss recording and OEM direct settlement, collapsing adjuster reconstruction cost and making parked collateral self-auditing. Autonomy vendors supply miles into the trust as a fungible input rather than an ownership substitute. Limited robotaxi rollouts confirm trip-cost optimization alone cannot unwind the bundle; parking it inside the industry's existing revenue geometry gives incumbents a reason to sponsor household de-anchoring.",
    "claimedDelta": "Households shed registrable-asset and spatial-anchor obligations without waiting for per-mile autonomy to beat monthly payments, while the car-dependency industry retains bundle economics instead of being bypassed by ride-hail disintermediation.",
